The Horatio Alger Association offers one of the largest need-based college scholarship programs in the country. It specifically assists high school students who have faced and overcome great obstacles. They seek students who have exhibited determination, integrity, and perseverance in overcoming adversity, as well as have critical financial need.

The application period for high school seniors pursuing bachelor's degree programs ends October 25th.

For more information, visit their website.

Class of 2024 -

LHS summer school has been canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic. If your student plans to take PE their Freshman year at LHS, during the regular school year, there is nothing you need to do.

If your student wants to earn one or both of their PE credits using Summer PE or a PE waiver, I’ve attached the policy for the class of 2024, only. This will need to be returned to Mrs. Tolliver by July 27, 2020. Please read carefully, and give me a call at 812-882-6168 if you have questions.

I hope all of you are well and we look forward to seeing you at Lincoln in August.

Mr. Combs

VCSC News
April 9 at 1:56 PM ·

Good morning all,

I certainly know that many of you are dealing with larger issues this morning from the storm. It is an E-Learning or counted day for education in the VCSC but this is secondary and quite frankly if it does not occur today, it does not occur.

Many of you are without power and this includes many of our staff members as well and they simply may not be available during the hours of 9AM to 2PM.

As we have learned with Covid-19, we have to be flexible. We just did not know that today that Covid-19 would become secondary for many of us and our attention would turn elsewhere and with this we must be flexible today and patient as we have too many people dealing with much larger issues than that of education and this is primarily related to the storm from last night.

Hopefully we will slowly start to return to what is the new normal for the time being, but today, education is far more secondary.

Hope you all are safe and with this, please stay safe!

Mr. Parsley

post_text:
The Indiana Commission for Higher Education is joining with INvestED Indiana to host a virtual FAFSA Frenzy event on Saturday, April 4.

Commission staff members will be answering common FAFSA questions and posting videos about the FAFSA. Follow along on social media with the #FAFSAFrenzyIN hashtag.

WHEN: Saturday, April 4, 2020, 1-3 p.m. (ET)
WHERE: Online: Learn More Indiana social media accounts on Facebook facebook.com/LearnMoreIN), Instagram (@LearnMoreIndiana) and Twitter (@LearnMoreIN)
By text and phone: To best serve the state, the Commission has split the state into eight regions. A full list of counties and associated numbers is available at www.learnmoreindiana.org. Reach INvestED any time at (317) 715-9007 for free assistance with the FAFSA.
¿Necesitas ayuda en español? Llame al 317-232-1072 o 317-617-0318.

Assistance with filing the FAFSA is open to anyone – regardless of age – planning to attend or thinking of attending college or some form of postsecondary education in the fall.

The Online Alice
March 30 at 12:50 AM ·

We have been getting a lot of questions about Chromebook chargers and we have some tips for you.

Amazon won't be shipping Chromebook chargers at this time (or at least until May 4th) because they aren't deemed essential. So, we found another site that is. Chromebook Parts is a site our Tech Department uses for all our needs and they have told us they are currently taking orders and shipping on time. We will attach the links below.

Senior – Junior  https://www.chromebookparts.com/Acer-C740-Power-Adapter-Grade-A-KP-0650H-006-146-p/ada-sng-103-2.htm
Freshman  https://www.chromebookparts.com/Acer-11-C732-Chromebook-AC-Power-Adapter-p/ada-sng-3288-7.htm

Also, remember that you don't need a Chromebook to access your school Google account. You just need a computer, tablet or smart device. As long as you can get to Google, you should be able to get to all of your items. Thank you again for your patience and if you have additional questions, please use our VCSC Helpline (vcschelp@vcsc.k12.in.us and 812-882-6376).

If you have additional questions and/or concerns, please feel free to contact us anytime on our VCSC Helpline. (vcschelp@vcsc.k12.in.us or 812-882-6376)

• Packets will be provided for those without eLearning capabilities.
• We are currently finalizing a plan for food service on the weeks of March 23rd and March 30th. Final information will be released early next week.

The Online Alice
March 10 at 5:45 PM ·

FYI: Parents of current juniors/incoming seniors: If you would like your student to receive state-required immunizations at LHS by Knox County immunization staff, please return the vaccination interest forms to the Lincoln school nurse by the end of this week. This will be done in April and interest forms were mailed home last week. If you return the form, we will send home further consent and insurance forms that will be required for your student to have these shots done at school. If you do NOT return these forms, we will not be able to vaccinate your student at LHS. You would then need to set up an appointment at the Immunization Clinic or with your doctor to have these immunizations done prior to the 2020-2021 school year. Please contact the school nurse if you have any questions. Thank you!

Applications for the 4th cohort of the Next Generation Hoosier Educators Scholarship are due this Saturday, November 30th, by midnight local time. As a reminder, the scholarship offers 200 students up to $30,000 over 4 years in exchange for agreeing to teach in Indiana for five years after graduation. Applicants must be in the top 20% of their class or have a top 20% ACT/SAT score.

To apply, students should visit LearnMoreIndiana.org/NextTeacher for full instructions.

Note that students must submit a nomination form with their application. It is important that students who want to apply over the Thanksgiving holiday have this completed before they leave school on Wednesday.

The LHS Boys Cross Country team finished 18th in the Brown County Semi-state today in very rainy and wet conditions. Alices were lead by Parker Mullins in 61st place followed by Keenan Clegg (98th), Trevor Robbins (134st), Nate Harris (135th), Blake Meade (145th) and Evan McGuire (154st). The Alices finish a great season highlighted by winning their first Sectional Championship since 1983. Special recognition to the three seniors, Parker Mullins, Trevor Robbins and Evan McGuire.

The best way to stay connected with College Goal Sunday Indiana is to check this website (http://collegegoalsunday.org/), and follow us on Twitter (@CGS_Indiana) and like us on Facebook (Indiana College Goal Sunday)!

post_text:
Indiana Homeland Security Foundation Scholarship
Indiana college students who volunteer with a public safety organization can now apply for the 2019 round of the Indiana Homeland Security Foundation Scholarship.
Eligible applicants include Indiana residents who are an incoming or continuing student who:
• Attends or will attend an accredited Indiana college
• Has a grade point average of 2.8 or higher on a 4.0 scale
• Volunteers at a public safety organization such as fire, law enforcement, emergency management or emergency medical services (validated by chief executive).
Applications are due by October 11, 2019, at 5:00pm EST. For more information, or to sign up for email updates about the Indiana Homeland Security Foundation Scholarship, visit the IDHS website. secure.in.gov/dhs/firecertification.htm
